The general accidential release program and chemical-specific prevention steps:  The facility complies with EPA's accident prevention rule.  The storage vessel and gas plant are also operated in compliance with the Texas Railroad CommissionStatewide rule 61 covering the operation of gasoline plants in the State of Texas.  We are currently in the process of upgrading the facility so that it will meet the standards provided in NFPA-58.  This upgrade is anticipated to be completed by June 21, 1999.

Five year accident history:  We have never had an accident involving a mixture of flammable liquids that caused deaths, injuries, property or environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering in place.

The emergency response program:  In the event of an emergency involving our pressurized storage vessel and refrigeration unit, it is our policy to notify the Houston County Fire Department and request that they respond to the emergency.  We have discussed this policy with the Houston County Fire Marshall.

Planned changes to improve safety:  A hazard review was performed at this facility on March 24, 1999.  The following changes are planned to improve safety at the facility:

1)  Place a wind sock at the facility for indication of wind direction in case of release;
2)  Remove all dead vegetation and wood pallets from around the pressurized storage vessel;
3)  Identify contents stored inside the pressurized vessel (i.e., Natral Gas Liquids);
4)  Place NFPA diamonds on the pressurized storage vessel;
5)  Replace loading hose.  the hose should be marked "For LP-Gas Service - Working Pressure 350 psi - Manufacturer's Name" and ledgible along full length of the hose.
6)  Provide housing/storage for the hose to prevent weathering;
7)  Cap end of hose when not in

 use to prevent entry of foreign objects;
8)  All openings and connections on the pressurized storage vessel should be capped to prevent entry of moisture and foreign objects;
9)  Vent stacks should be placed over pressure relief devices to prevent impingement of vapors upon the vessel in case of a release;
10)  Vent stacks should have protective caps or closures to prevent entry of foreign matter or moisture;
11)  Weep holes should be placed at the base of vent stacks for moisture drainage;
12)  Internal relief valves should be pressure tested to ensure proper operation;
13)  Place a temperaturee guage on the vessel so that the vessel temperature may be monitored;
14)  Replace existing manual fluid level indicator with an automatic fluid level indicator;
15)  Replace manufacturer's name plate with a ledgible name plate, if possible;
16)  Provide fire extinguishers with protective cabinets near the loading area;
17)  Provide chock blocks for loading trucks;
18)  Paint and label all liquid and vapor lines associated with covered process.
